(574, 111, 'tl_article', 352, 1505926910, 'text', 'a:2:{s:4:\"unit\";s:2:\"h1\";s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"The economy of Thailand\";}', '<p>Tourism contributes significantly to the Thai economy, and the industry has benefited from the baht\'s depreciation and Thailand\'s stability. Tourist arrivals in 2002 reflected a 7.3 percent increase from the previous year. Tourism makes a larger contribution to Thailand\'s economy than that of any other Asian nation. Tourists come to Thailand for a variety of reasons, primarily for recreation on its beaches. With ongoing insurgency in the deep South, Bangkok has seen a large increase in tourism in recent years.[nbsp]<br><br>An increase in tourism from other Asian countries has contributed to the country\'s economy, although the baht has recently strengthened relative to other currencies. In 2007, about 14[nbsp]million tourists visited Thailand. The tourism sector includes a sex industry, although prostitution is illegal in Thailand.[nbsp]<br>The easing of the[nbsp]monetary crisis, the renewed growth of the[nbsp]Chinese economy, the relatively stable internal political situation following the[nbsp]2008Thai political crisis[nbsp]and the[nbsp]2009 flu pandemic[nbsp]having less of an impact than initially feared changed the tourism outlook.<br><br>Thailand experienced a 16 percent decrease in international visitors during the first six months of 2009, but the remainder of the year saw a return of foreign tourists (with a marked increase in November and December). The number of tourists in 2009 was estimated at nearly 14[nbsp]million, a decrease of 4 percent from 2008.[72]</p>', '', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'above', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 0, 'ascending', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', 4, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', '', 0, 300, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', NULL, '', 'a:2:{i:0;s:0:\"\";i:1;s:9:\"col-md-12\";}', 'a:2:{i:0;s:0:\"\";i:1;s:0:\"\";}', '', '', '', 'as