(44, 56, 1506266642, 'Almeria', 'http://localhost/ContaoMeta.0.1/index.php/news-archive-travels/almeria.html', 'Almeria My time in this beautiful place Home Almeria After spending two weeks in Orihuela costa, in the middle of crazy-nowhere town, I decided to come back to Alicante for a few days and then head off for Almeria. I had seen that apartments were very cheap in Almeria and had heard that food was also very tasty and cheap too. I decided this was the place for me, and so it was my home for about 3 months. Barking mad BnB For the first week of my stay in Almeria, I decided I would go for another AirBnB and so I booked a nice looking room with a Chilean lady in Almeria. It was alright for the first few days, I got used to the annoying dog and its barking. But with no friends in Almeria and no beach to chill at, I become bored quickly. I started to think about that beautiful girl I met on the bus and wonder why she wasn\'t calling me. To take my mind off all this I went walking around the small and beautiful city of Almeria. My first apartment with Spanish people Within 3 days I had had enough of this woman and her fucking dogs. As if one loud scraggly dog wasn\'t enough to annoy her guests, the bloody woman had to go out and get more dogs. She said she used some app for dog-sitting, basically taking care of other peoples dogs whilst they aren\'t at home, and for this she got a bit of money. I searched around online a bit, in Spain you can\'t just send a message over a website to a landlord, you have to call them. This was a bit scary for me as it was actually my first time every speaking Spanish on the phone. It\'s always way harder on the telephone for some reason. The Spanish part was horribly embarassing, but she spoke English and told me to come for a viewing. I went, I liked the tennants, they liked me, so I moved in that very day (and paid the rent 3 days later) Apartment life My new apartment was just amazing, I feel so lucky to have lived there for such a low price. Almeria is such a wonderful city, so unspoiled by tourism like so many other parts of Spain. It\'s so Spanish and so well preserved that you feel like you\'re living in the 1980\'s or 1990\'s. Almeria is the capital of the Almeria region, which grows so much fruit and vegetables that they export around 70% of it to the rest of Europe This all meant that food in Almeria was VERY cheap. Noy only had I found a beautiful, preserved and cheap city, I had found a 200 euro a month apartment on the beach with a weed dealer neighbour and beautiful girls recently visiting. Begining work on the new SamLernen On coming to Almeria, I had the intention of setting aside some time to really crack the books and learn. I wanted to build SamLernen. I wanted it to be big and impressive, I wanted to learn everything there was to learn about web design and development so I could achieve this. In Almeria I spend countless days indoors getting high and learning all about web development/coding and more about computer science in general. Computer science has always been my second academic passion, alongside languages. Contao Demo, , AlmeriaFountains.JPG, IMG-20170308-WA0028.jpg, IMG_1913.JPG, IMG_1925.JPG, IMG_1946.JPG, IMG_1958.JPG', 19.04, 'f6c2f2ea1c5fcbf9e5b92c22d3d2c080', '', 0x30, 'en'),
(45, 56, 1506266642, 'Alicante', 'http://localhost/ContaoMeta.0.1/index.php/news-archive-travels/alicante.html', 'Alicante I love this beautiful city in Spain Home Alicante Ok so Alicante is where everything got a bit crazy. I arrived by train from Valencia because yet again I was being a posh tourist and decided to stay in a hostel. I thought it would be a good idea to do something like a rotation; one week hostel in one place, next week AirBnb in next place. The hostel was a really nice and colorful youth hostel which had a real party atmosphere. It had a lot of graffiti on the walls from guests and had a terrace with some sick psychadelic artwork. It was still winter time so there were few tourists and the prices were low. Prices per night at the hostel fluctuate between 13 and 20 euros a night between Summer and Winter. New friends at the hostel Really nice hostel, great parties and tonnes of girls that want to spend time with me. Above is one, we walked up to the castle together. I think her name was Cleopatra. Nice girl. I\'ve been thinking of returning there to make some more contacts. I\'m always searching for other digital nomads who are into teaching, translating and web design/development and I met one of my best friends, Toby, at the hostel. He is also a web developer and travels around Spain on his money he earns from that. Alicante beach After a night of partying at the hostel, drinking lots of alcohol and smoking lots of weed from the local cannabis assosciation, we would hit the beach. It was still winter, but midday temperatures could reach up to 18 degrees. The water was still way too cold to swim in though, although I remember one guy from England (also called Sam) went into the cold water and came out freezing. Funny I mention him, because at one time in my 2 weeks in this hostel there were 5 guys all from England called Sam More Skype troubles Of course all this partying meant that I had a hard time with my Skype lessons. I smoked so much ganja that I began to forget the lessons I had that day or I would just oversleep from the night before. I knew that it couldn\'t go on like this or I would risk losing my clients that I liked. Again at the hostel, I had the problem of having terrible Wi-Fi, meaning I had to go out and search a place that had it better. The troubled in Spain is that most cafes don\'t have Wi-Fi and most of them don\'t want it either. Spanish streets are filled with traditional, basic Spanish cafeterias that have lots of old people in them and look very uninviting to tourists. The Spanish like it this way, they don\'t want uncivilized white tourists (\"giris\" in Spanish) infecting their cafes. I eventually found a nice modern cafe called Canada Coffe which was run by two Canadian guys. They had super Wi-Fi and nice tea so I decided to call this place my new internet home. Off for a \"workation\" My next port of call was a strange place in the absolute middle of nowhere. A very strange place in Spain that is so un-Spanish that I have a hard time calling it Spain. I was leaving with my friend Toby to focus on our online businesses away from the party life of Alicante at the hostel. Contao Demo, , IMG_1759.JPG, IMG_1798.JPG, IMG_1820.JPG, MeBeach.jpg, 16864216_10155460463787289_1205234521501558765_n.jpg, IMG_1751.JPG', 18.79, '556e270165a213b57b5a41c9d79a9436', '', 0x30, 'en'),
(46, 56, 1506266643, 'Valencia', 'http://localhost/ContaoMeta.0.1/index.php/news-archive-travels/valencia-yeah-im-so-cool.html', 'Valencia The next destination Home Arrival in Valencia Being the tourist with money that I was back then, I bought myself a train ticket to Valencia. Nowadays I would have taken a bus or car sharing (using BlaBlaCar) or maybe hitchhiked as trains are an unnecessary luxury when you\'re a traveller who wants to go on travelling forever.It was a cool journey however, we went through the Catalan countryside and then along the coast. The Valencian countryside is very flat with lots of deserts and mountains. Quite a cool place to shoot a film I think My host I rented a room for a week in an apartment in Valencia. I booked it through AirBnB, a relatively new, but verrrrry successful online app for holiday rentals. My host was a nice dude from Chile, he was into all the same rap music as me, so we chilled and had a barbeque on his roof terrace...in February. His flate mate was also great, for some reason I can\'t forget his face. He was also from Chile,but didn\'t work, rather just relaxed, played guitar and spent time with his son. He was so warm and friendly. Exploring Valencia by bike The next day, I went to the beautiful center of Valencia to go and rent myself a bike. On the first day I didn\'t find a bike rental shop, so I just walked around and took photos. The center, just like Barcelona, is a treat for the eyes. It\'s filled with traditional architcture, ancient remains and historical artifacts. The day after that I got my bike and took to the outskirts of the city. I first headed to the beach, which was much further away than I thought, I ended up in poor rural countryside very quick, It was like going from 2017 to 1917. I love how how such a part of the city area is so well preserved. After cycling for an hour I got to the beach. First cycled through the massive harbour complex and then onto the sprawling empty beach. It was too cold to swim so it was like a ghost town on the promenade. I took so many photos on those days, it felt so powerful and fantastic to cycle around a new country. Getting out all that bottled energy. Finding places to work Instead of taking time to enjoy my travels, I kept on giving my Skype lessons as if going to a new country to explore was an everyday thing for me. Well, I had moved from Germany to England and then to Spain all in the span of just 6 months. In Barcelona, I found it pretty difficult to keep up with my Skype lessons. I didn\'t have my macbook back then, just my shitty old laptop and my Ipad, I went to cafes and tried, but often times the coffee machines or the street noises were too loud and I had to cancel the lesson, other times I was just way too stoned. In Valencia, I didn\'t have this problem so much as I was staying in a quiet AirBnb with good, stable WIFI and not using the crappy hostel WIFI that a bunch of wannabe travellers are clogging up with their Facebook posts about how great ( *shit ) their holiday really is. Next destination My next destination was the sunny city of Alicante, 3 or 4 hours to the South of Valencia. It was a city I had been to before with my parents on my earlier travels as a child. My ultimate goal is to get to most Southern tip of Spain (Gibraltar) and then travel Portugal and head up North. Let\'s see how long that will take Contao Demo, , IMG_1684.JPG, IMG_1690.JPG, IMG_1691.JPG, IMG_1693.JPG, IMG_1694.JPG, IMG_1695.JPG, IMG_1700.JPG, IMG_1704.JPG, IMG_1726.JPG', 19.65, '045e77fc37e0073282cd2446e1d07cd6', '', 0x30, 'en'),
(47, 56, 1506266644, 'Arrival in Barcelona, Spain', 'http://localhost/ContaoMeta.0.1/index.php/news-archive-travels/arrival-in-spain.html', 'Arrival in Barcelona, Spain It all started here Home Previous Next Arrival in Spain After months of wondering what I should do with my life, I finally decided to book a one way ticket to Barcelona, it only cost me 50 euros with my big new travel bag! I had a last meal with my family at a mexican restaurant and took the 6 hour long train to London airport the next day. At the aiport it was so rainy and wet, making the arrival in Barcelona so much nicer (even though it was at night) Adventures in Barcelona In Barcelona I stayed in a small youth hostel near the center. I enjoy my stay quite a lot, although it was a very quiet hostel and it was the winter season, so very few tourists. I mostly saw city travellers, many from Asia, they didn\'t talk to us Western people, just went out in the day in their expensive clothes and went to bed early at night. I did get to know a hot Chinese chick though. She was nice Exploring the city of Barcelona I rented a bike for 5 days or so and explored the entire city. The city was so big and magnificent that It took 5 days to really explore it all. It\'s so damn beautiful, it was totally worth it. Barcelona is a very interesting part of Spain, it\'s the capital of Catalonia, a region of Spain with it\'s own distinct culture and language seeking it\'s independence. You can see nationanism everywhere, almost every apartment building has between 3 - 30 catalan flags hanging from the windows The Cannabis club I met a great friend there, another digital nomad from Israel who is a software developer, he spends 4 months to a year in every country he visits and works all around the world. He was so smart, I felt humbled that we become great friends. He introduced me to one of the best Cannabis Clubs in the city. In Spain, marijuana is legal to buy in licenses assosiacions. I bought some verrrry nice weed and got very stoned for a few days. The city just got 3x more beautiful. Time to leave After a week of doing this I got bored. I had seen the whole city and the hostel was getting boring with it\'s lame guests. I booked myself a train ticket to Valencia and a stay in an AirBnb for a week. Contao Demo, , IMG_1533.JPG, IMG_1540.JPG, IMG_1548.JPG, IMG_1603.JPG, IMG_1611.JPG', 17.8, 'aa17c8267ea1e0b13f6036abe110bff0', '', 0x30, 'en');
